14 "14-2-510.
15 (a) Venue in proceedings against a corporation shall be determined in accordance with the
16 pertinent constitutional and statutory provisions of this state in effect as of July 1, 1989, or
17 thereafter.
18 (b) Each domestic corporation and each foreign corporation authorized to transact business
19 in this state shall be deemed to reside and to be subject to venue as follows:
20 (1) In civil proceedings generally, in the county of this state where the corporation
21 maintains its registered office; or if the corporation fails to maintain a registered office,
22 it shall be deemed to reside in the county where its last named registered office or
23 principal office, as shown by the records of the Secretary of State, was maintained;
24 (2) In actions based on contracts, in that county in this state where the contract to be
25 enforced was made or is to be performed, if the corporation has an office and transacts
26 business in that county;
27 (3) In actions for damages because of torts, wrong, or injury done, in the county where
28 the cause of action originated, if the corporation has an office and transacts business in
29 that county;
30 (4) In actions for damages because of torts, wrong, or injury done, in the county where
31 the cause of action originated. If venue is based solely on this paragraph, the defendant
32 shall have the right to remove the action to the county in Georgia where the defendant
33 maintains its principal place of business. A notice of removal shall be filed within 45
34 days of service of the summons. Upon motion by the plaintiff filed within 45 days of the
35 removal, the court to which the case is removed may remand the case to the original court
36 if it finds that removal is improper under the provisions of this paragraph. Upon the
37 defendant's filing of a notice of removal, the 45 day time period for filing such notice
38 shall be tolled until the remand, the entry of an order by the court determining that the
39 removal is valid, or the expiration of the time period for the plaintiff to file a motion
40 challenging the removal, whichever occurs first; and
